issue.body:
Version: current `main` (`13a1c9dc9`)

I think there is a bug in the multipart parser used by `Response.formData()` / `Request.formData()`.

If a part body contains the boundary text inline, the parser seems to treat that as a real multipart delimiter even when it is not on a delimiter line.

Minimal repro:

```ts
const boundary = "AaB03x";

const body =
  `--${boundary}\r\n` +
  `Content-Disposition: form-data; name="file"; filename="x.txt"\r\n` +
  `Content-Type: text/plain\r\n` +
  `\r\n` +
  `before--${boundary}after\r\n` +
  `--${boundary}--\r\n`;

const res = new Response(body, {
  headers: {
    "content-type": `multipart/form-data; boundary=${boundary}`,
  },
});

const fd = await res.formData();
const file = fd.get("file") as File;

console.log(await file.text());
```

Expected:

```txt
before--AaB03xafter
```

Actual:

The current parser logic looks like it will stop the part at the embedded `--AaB03x` and truncate the content.

From reading `ext/fetch/21_formdata.js`, the relevant part seems to be that the parser advances on raw `--boundary` byte matches inside state 2, but does not verify that the match is actually a multipart delimiter line like `\r\n--boundary\r\n` or `\r\n--boundary--`.

Relevant code:
- `ext/fetch/21_formdata.js` around the `boundaryIndex` matching in `MultipartParser.parse()`

If I am reading this correctly, valid multipart bodies can be misparsed whenever uploaded content happens to contain boundary-like bytes.
